  "text": "Because of concerns over adequate levels of statistical power to detect significant effects, we combined the supervisor and job analyst data (N ϭ 48) and interpreted one-tailed significance tests. Statistical power was 53% to detect a medium effect (d ϭ .50) and 86% to detect a large effect (d ϭ .80; p Ͻ .05, one-tailed; [CITATION_1] . The range of effect sizes found in the incumbent sample suggests that we had adequate statistical power to detect significant differences if such differences existed. Although we expected to find no differences (in essence accepting the null hypothesis), [CITATION_2] have suggested that there are circumstances when this is warranted. The supplemental study used the same measures, administered in the same fashion, with a similar type of sample, which did produce differences among incumbents. This suggests that the supplemental analyses were sensitive enough to produce and detect differences if they were present among supervisors and job analysts.",
